               <t:note>
                  <t:date type="foundation" cert="low">17th-18th century</t:date>
                  <t:desc type="foundation">Local priests believe that it was built by 
                     <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS4015Fasilada">
                        <t:roleName type="title">ʾaṣe</t:roleName> Fāsiladas</t:persName> in the <t:date>17th
                        century</t:date>, while, according to <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS2916Bruce">James
                           Bruce</t:persName>, it was built by <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS5617IyasuII">ʾIyāsu
                        II</t:persName>, meaning it was built only in the <t:date>18th century</t:date>.</t:desc>
                  <t:ab type="history">ʾAzazo Takla Hāymānot is one of the so-called 44 churches of
                        <t:placeName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LOC3577Gondar">Gondar</t:placeName>. It is located in the town
                     of <t:placeName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LOC1669Azazo">ʾAzazo</t:placeName>, 13 km southwest of
                        <t:placeName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LOC3577Gondar">Gondar</t:placeName>. This church played an
                     important role in the history of Ethiopian monasticism: following the burning of <t:placeName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LOC2297DabraL">Dabra Libānos</t:placeName> in <t:date>1532</t:date> and the decision to move the monastic community north in the lake <t:placeName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LOC5888Tana">Ṭānā</t:placeName> area, the monastic
                     community of <t:placeName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LOC2297DabraL">Dabra Libānos</t:placeName> finally settled in <t:placeName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LOC1669Azazo">ʾAzazo</t:placeName>.
                     </t:ab>
                  <t:ab type="description">ʾAzazo Takla Hāymānot is located at the centre of a
                     hilltop, surrounded by a courtyard and a circular stone wall with a square
                     tower.</t:ab> 
                     <t:ab type="tabot">At one hand of the courtyard, there is a semi-circular domed castle where, according to local tradition, the tābot of <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS6819Mary">Mary</t:persName> of <t:placeName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LOC2297DabraL">Dabra Libānos</t:placeName> was first installed when it was moved from <t:placeName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LOC2297DabraL">Dabra Libānos</t:placeName> to <t:placeName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LOC1669Azazo">ʾAzazo</t:placeName>, although the tābot's movements are actually quite complicated to reconstruct.</t:ab>
                     <t:measure quantity="1"/>
                       </t:note>
            </t:place>
            
